    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Pieter Nanninck to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 22 August [1538])</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">1. Nanninck is happy that Oláh is well; so many have
                            been lost in this awful year of the plague. Rutger Ressen is quite sick
                            and has only started to get better recently, while Nanninck is dizzy and
                            nauseous. 2. He has brought this book into the world more like a
                            premature baby, he has not really completed it. So he has taken his
                            Demosthenes out from under the press and modified it for the fourth time
                            already, although he is still only halfway through. But now everything
                            is going well, and the translation will be worthy of Oláh; it will be
                            published before Oláh leaves.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Idem Nannius domino Nicolao <del corresp="Olahus">Olacho</del><add
                        corresp="Olahus" type="corr">Olaho</add> salutem plurimam.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">[1.] Vidimus in litteris<note xml:id="note.1">We do not know these
                        letters.</note> ad <persName>Iacobum Danum</persName><note xml:id="note.2"
                        >Jakob Jespersen.</note> mihi et <persName>Rutgero Rescio</persName><note
                        xml:id="note.3">Rutger Ressen.</note> salutem adscriptam, quae res nobis
                    iucundissima fuit, multo tamen iucundius, quod tuam valetudinem nullo morbo
                    attentatam audivimus. In hoc tam <del corresp="editor">tam</del> pestifero anno
                    infiniti ubique pereunt. <persName>Rutgerus</persName> periculosissime aegrotat,
                    hactenus cum ipsius et omnium desperatione nunc aliquanto commodius habet, satis
                    tamen res <del corresp="Olahus">anticipiti</del><add corresp="Olahus"
                        type="corr">ancipiti</add> loco est. Ego vertigine cerebri laboravi cum
                    fastidio stomachi perpetuo, in studiis nec publicis, </p>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.3">nec privatis quicquam feliciter potui. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">[2.] Hunc infelicem libellum abortivi potius, quam edidi, ad id
                    coactus magnis amicorum cohortationibus, qui me ingentia sperare iubebant.
                    Hactenus nihil apparet, quid autem futurum sit, nescio, id saltem gaudeo, quod
                    amici me suis postulatis contumacem non senserunt. <choice>
                        <orig>Demosthenem tuum</orig>
                        <supplied>Demosthenes tuus</supplied>
                    </choice>, quem <choice>
                        <orig>paulo</orig>
                        <supplied>prelo</supplied>
                    </choice> subieceram, ita mihi placuit, ut eum retractum ab officina
                        <persName>Rutgeri</persName>, <quote xml:id="quote.1">non in spongiam
                        incumbere, ut Aiax ille Augusti,</quote><note type="quote"
                        xml:id="note.quote.1">Suet. <hi rend="italic">De vitis caesarum</hi>, Div.
                        Aug. 85: “respondit, Aiacem suum in spongeam incubuisse”.</note><note
                        xml:id="note.4">Frans van Cranevelt liked citing this line, see Ep. 585. and
                        Ep. 592. Cap.
                        2.<ref>olahus.tei.15370428_1</ref></note><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15371004_1</ref>
                    sed Latine sordibus <quote xml:id="quote.2">naufragium pati</quote><note
                        type="quote" xml:id="note.quote.2">Sen. <hi rend="italic">Herc. Oet.</hi>
                        118.</note> coegenti iam quarto illum transfero, et ultra dimidium
                    progressus sum. Arrident nunc melius omnia; certe aut erit te digna translatio,
                    aut immoriar operi, id statum est, nec aliud <choice>
                        <orig>manus in summa</orig>
                        <supplied>in manus sumam</supplied>
                    </choice>, priusquam illum <hi rend="italic">Antheum</hi> confecero.<note
                        xml:id="note.5">Agathon’s tragedies, for example <hi rend="italic"
                            >Antheus</hi>, continued in the footstep of Euripides’ tragedies. Not
                        long before, Nanninck had translated Euripides’ <hi rend="italic"
                            >Andromache</hi>, see Ep. 590.<ref>olahus.tei.15370928_1</ref></note>
                    Generosissime et Magnificentissime, peream pessime, si mihi quicquam difficilius
                    expertus sum; non remorantur sententiae, sed cupio in Latinis non nihil
                    respondere Demosthenicis virtutibus, id non nisi extremo et assiduo conatu
                    impetrare possum. Ante tamen tuum reditum spero librum evulgatum iri. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.5">De rebus novis turpe est ad te scribere, cuius fidelissimae
                    conscientiae reges et monarchae sua arcana committunt. Faxit Deus, ut et
                    Hungariam et te talem videamus, <choice>
                        <orig>quarum</orig>
                        <supplied>qualem</supplied>
                    </choice> regia <choice>
                        <orig>tuarum</orig>
                        <supplied>tuorum</supplied>
                    </choice> progenies et tua virtus <choice>
                        <orig>meretur</orig>
                        <supplied>merenter</supplied>
                    </choice>, et optant omnes, praesertim eruditi. Bene vale, Meum Unicum
                    Praesidium et vere Maecenas. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.6"><placeName>Lovanii</placeName> XI. Kalendas Septembris.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
